I don't often comment but I do when I have something to say. I think these guys are being very responsible entrepreneurs by putting their established situations first and not diving into the unknown risking everything and potentially losing all they have over an idea. It's clear to me that these two are responsible and still passionate about their product, it's a damn good one! Shame on the sharks for cutting into them for having a safety net. I know somebody who put everything he had on the line trying to get a business going and he just lost his house and put his family life into complete termoil because of his irresponsible behaviour. Not a very smart thing to do and might I say a pretty selfish thing to do when you have a family. I can't stand behind their logic. It's easy for them to sit back now in their ivory towers with their comfort and millions while they point the finger and criticize these two for having a safety net, makes me sick. Just because it worked out for them doesn't mean it always will for everyone. A person has to eat and feed their family in the meantime, that's what matters. This is yet another classic tale of the rich being completely removed from common sense and reality. Don't get me wrong, I'm glad that it worked out for them but their projects could have just as easily blown up in their faces while their families would have taken the brunt. Terrible advice on their part. I'm out.

Just my opinion like Janine & Steve I took three years no wage while starting my business, but I think the sharks are off point here, this business is not Boost Juice it far less complicated, IMO it's a novelty product that will sell well and almost autonomously in the local market *maybe even abroad. The only reason these guys would benefit going full time is if they had a slew of products lined up that could be as popular as this over the next five or ten years, this is literally the perfect side gig you could almost automate the whole process from factory to buyer. No chance I'd be quitting work for this one if I had a family at home.

At that point, that's the point of the business, when you like your actual job more... because it makes more money?
It's why Steve said it's an "attitude" thing, not a business thing per se.

Investors also played it safe because they kept their jobs. It's pretty obvious how niche the product is, and it feels more like a gimmick more than anything. Compared to other products which are REVOLUTIONARY, this one is just a meh product. It's good, but it's not something everyone will buy. With that, it's pretty hard to throw everything away for that product. 
They know that the product is kind of in a "volatile" state, wherein it might go bad, or it might go good... so they didn't take the risk to commit full time.

Y'all, I'm pretty sure the center of the legality/nutrition impasse is this: The bar uses INGREDIENTS which are proven to have beneficial properties. The bar's FORMULA has  been tested for the specific properties claimed. The syntax of the packaging text implied the formula/_whole bar_ had data behind it, which it didn't. A simple wording tweak is all it really takes to resolve that, though, for sure. Idk about laws in Australia specifically, but going off my US-based understanding of enforcement norms and some language-geekness, that's what I've got.

For an example of why this matters, consider that, like ... hmm ... Iodine (if I recall right) binds to lots of metals, so one shouldn't use a metal spoon to stir a smoothie if taking a liquid iodine supplement for instance, so someone could make a formula for a supplement that contains iodine but also unthinkingly put a bunch of iron in it too, and then they could accurately label it as having an  that yields the benefits of iodine or whatever (this is a really crappy example because iodine is more of a lacking-it-messes-you-up thing than a taking-extra-helps-with-something thing, just work with me here), but wouldn't be able to reasonably claim the whole  yields those benefits, because if tested, it wouldn't, because the iodine would be all bound up or something. Grain of salt this whole example. Pretend the elements are made up. Point is, stuff can cancel other stuff out or synergize badly or do other weird stuff, and clear specific syntax matters a lot in general and especially when it comes to health facts

If you frequent supplement stores, you may notice that major products/brands come and go, there are two reasons

1) supplement companies fall under legal scrutiny regularly. The often operate as llcs and so when thecompany gets sued into oblivion they file bankruptcy, and then the owners create a new llc, slightly tweak the products and come back branded differently
2) health trends change rapidly, and people follow the trends more than the science. The trouble with that is it leads to the the aforementioned legal scrutiny. For example, lots of products right now have heavy ‘keto’ branding, but if you look at the nutritional info, a lot of these products contain enough carbs in a single serving to kick you out of ketosis. The industry is rapidly moving from trend to trend, so false advertisement is a consistent problem.

So for everyone debating about this product and the misleading and illegal claim on the package. The chocolate does still exist and sells well however sans the claim. The issue is this science supports that those ingredients are associated with improvements but there are a lot of questions that must be answered starting with the study the claim was pulled from. How long was the study they looked at. A longitudinal study (over the course of many many years often decades) does very little to support the claim on the back as their claim would be seen as a happening over a short period of time. Additionally they need to ensure none of their other additives disrupt this process adding together 3 good things that should do what you say does not mean it will. Its not researched or supported. Yet another issue that comes into play is dose is there a certain amount needed to be taken get this effect? Its a serious and important question. The fact that they dropped it from their marketing says that it was either too much to do the research so they didn't bother or they did it and it came up negative.
